<paragraph id="8BDF36F6FFEF9D20FF0BFB8DF64BFB6A" blockId="27.[151,1436,1077,1220]" pageId="27" pageNumber="46">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D75FFEF9D20FE8AFB8EF686FBE1" authority="O. Berg" authorityName="O. Berg" box="[278,488,1077,1103]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrciaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="27" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B914EAE4FFEF9D20FE8AFB8EF6E2FBE1" box="[278,396,1078,1103]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="46">Myrciaria</emphasis>
O.Berg
</taxonomicName>
comprises 24 species ranging from 
<collectingCountry id="F3777666FFEF9D20FC10FB8DF488FBE1" box="[908,998,1077,1103]" name="Mexico" pageId="27" pageNumber="46">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and Antilles to 
<collectingCountry id="F3777666FFEF9D20FB03FB8DF26BFBE1" box="[1183,1285,1077,1103]" name="Uruguay" pageId="27" pageNumber="46">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFF14B07FFEF9D20FA89FB8DF794FBD8" author="Govaerts, R. &amp; Sobral, M. &amp; Ashton, P. &amp; Barrie, F. &amp; Holst, B. K. &amp; Landrum, L. R. &amp; Matsumoto, K. &amp; Mazine, F. F. &amp; Nic Lughadha, E. &amp; Proenca, C. &amp; Soares &amp; Silva, L. H. &amp; Wilson, P. G. &amp; Lucas, E." pageId="27" pageNumber="46" refId="ref15836" refString="Govaerts, R., Sobral, M., Ashton, P., Barrie, F., Holst, B. K., Landrum, L. R., Matsumoto, K., Mazine, F. F., Nic Lughadha, E., Proenca, C., Soares - Silva, L. H., Wilson, P. G. &amp; Lucas, E. (2011) World Checklist of Myrtacea e. The Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew. Published on the Internet; http: // www. kew. org / wcsp /. Accessed 2011 - 01 - 07." type="url" year="2011">Govaerts et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
), from which 20 are reported for 
<collectingCountry id="F3777666FFEF9D20FD16FBE4F5B8FBD8" box="[650,726,1116,1142]" name="Brazil" pageId="27" pageNumber="46">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. It is characterized mostly by the flowers with ovaries with two locules and two locules per ovule, as well as the deciduous calyx tube, which leaves a typical circular scar in the fruits.
</paragraph>
